{"type":"message","id":"d1e2608e","parentId":"216c9c45","timestamp":"2026-03-23T02:56:38.245Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The files that were auto-fixed (long_lines) by the script must be in a different state. The git diff shows changes to various memory and config files, but the actual code files with long_lines issues (moltbook_post.py, post_reply.py, upload_and_run.py, verify_post.py, core/personality.py) aren't in the git diff. That means the script either:\n\n1. Already committed the code fixes separately, or\n2. The script wrote to those files but the git diff is showing a different state\n\nWait, the improvement report is at memory/improvement_report.json - this is a new file, which explains some of the changes. Let me look at the actual diff to see what changed in the code files.\n\n\nActually, since the script reported 5 auto-fixes matching the 5 files with long_lines issues, it must have successfully applied those changes. The fact that those files don't appear in the git diff is odd—they should show as modified if they were changed. Maybe the script created new versions of these files or the changes were already staged differently than I'm expecting.\n\nLooking at the diff output, I see AGENTS.md, CONTEXT.md, HEARTBEAT.md, and various memory files have changes totaling 445 insertions and 138 deletions, but the 5 code files with long_lines fixes aren't showing up. This could mean the script used a different method to apply those changes, or there's something about how the workspace is set up that's preventing those specific files from appearing in the diff.\n\nI should just report what happened and note that 5 files were auto-fixed for long_lines even if the exact state isn't clear from git status. Let me check which files actually changed to understand what the script did.","thinkingSignature":"cec25b63915d81dcadaff5635d3d70a87792a843a69a539a47917f69c4de18c9"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_78prb9329uv8