{"type":"message","id":"c7edda9a","parentId":"2f17e554","timestamp":"2026-03-23T02:57:43.141Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue. The `apply_fixes` function has this logic:\n\n```python\nif len(line) > 120 and \"http\" not in line and not line.strip().startswith(\"#\"):\n    # Try to wrap at a space\n    if \"    \" in line:\n        parts = line.split(\"    \", 1)\n        new_lines.append(parts[0].strip())\n        new_lines.append(\"    \" + parts[1].strip())\n    else:\n        new_lines.append(line)\n```\n\nSo:\n- moltbook_post.py: The long lines are string literals (content strings) without \"http\" and without \"    \" (indentation spaces), so they get appended unchanged.\n\n\n- post_reply.py line 19: Also a long string literal without \"http\" and without \"    \" (it's 4 spaces indentation at the start), so it doesn't match the wrapping condition.\n- verify_post.py: Same pattern - long string literals with 4 spaces indentation but the condition checks for `if \"    \"` which would be true... Let me re-check. Actually it says `if \"    \" in line` - but the indentation spaces would be at the start. If the line is `    \"content\": \"\"\"...` then `\"    \"` would indeed be in it, so it would try to split. But wait, the issue is that these strings contain 4 spaces somewhere in them, which means the wrapping logic would trigger even though it shouldn't for string content.\n- upload_and_run.py: Lines with `http` (line 69) and lines with specific formatting that don't match the wrapping condition.\n- core\\personality.py: Line 252 is 121 characters which is only 1 over the threshold.\n\nThe auto-fixes are failing because the wrapping logic is too simplistic - it tries to split on \"    \" (4 spaces) but these are string literals and JSON content where that split doesn't make sense. The fixes weren't applied correctly.\n\nThe real issue is that the script didn't actually auto-fix anything. Looking at the 5 files it was supposed to fix, none of the long lines qualify for wrapping since they either contain \"http\", have string content without proper indentation to split on, or are just barely over the limit. The \"5 auto-fixed\" count likely came from the script's reporting mechanism rather than actual fixes applied.","thinkingSignature":"f37e3ef5f737f65d92a2d4fc2a531fcf5db182aaddba43e9a550f610f853e48a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_04pxsaxobol6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace && python -c \"\nfiles = ['moltbook_post.py', 'post_reply.py', 'verify_post.py', 'upload_and_run.py', r'core\\personality.py']\nfor f in files:\n    with open(f, 'rb') as fh:\n        raw = fh.read()\n    lines = raw.split(b'\\r\\n')\n    for i, l in enumerate(lines, 1):\n        if len(l) > 120:\n            has_http = b'http' in l\n            starts_hash = l.strip().startswith(b'#')\n            has_quad_space = b'    ' in l\n            print(f'{f}:{i} len={len(l)} http={has_http} hash={starts_hash} quad={has_quad_space}')\n            print(f'  first 60: {l[:60]}')\n\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":9285,"output":699,"cacheRead":11099,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21083,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774234652635}}
