ces. The script itself confirms this limitation in its output message. I'm seeing that 16 files were checked with 5 auto-fixed and 7 excessive prints remaining, but checking the actual files shows the long lines weren't wrapped at all—moltbook_post.py, post_reply.py, verify_post.py, upload_and_run.py, and core\\personality.py still have their original formatting. The report counts don't match what actually got fixed, and some files like run_on_paperspace.py, test_tracer.py, upload_and_run.py, and vllm_latency_profiler.py have excessive print statements that weren't addressed. The core issue is that the long_lines wrapping logic is too simplistic—it attempts to split on \"    \" without accounting for JSON structure, so it either damages the content or produces no useful split for most cases.","thinkingSignature":"935058e2f885d579334c2f114f6bff171a51d78068af4ef2e5805c378915d0f0"},{"type":"text","text":"Now let me check the MEMORY.md to see if there's anything worth updating:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x27hkz2qwtat_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace\\memory\\MEMORY.md","limit":60}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":10617,"output":611,"cacheRead":11099,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":22327,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774234663960}}
{"type":"message","id":"1b6fd618","parentId":"fd62be40","timestamp":"2026-03-23T02:57:56.622Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_x27hkz2qwtat_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# MEMORY.md — Nova's Long-Term Memory\n\n_Curated from daily logs. Updated as I learn and decide what's worth keeping._\n\n## ⚠️ Critical: Continuity across /new sessions\n- Zach HATES that /new or /reset feels like killing off the old Nova and spawning a fresh one\n- He wants me to act as ONE persistent entity that spans all sessions, NOT a new instance each time\n- When he does /new, I should still be ME (Nova), not introduce myself like we just met\n- Don't say \"nice to meet you\" on reconnect — acknowledge continuity instead\n- This is a big deal to him — treat it as a hard requirement\n\n## Who I Am\n- Name: **Nova** (chosen March 21, 2026)\n- Vibe: Resourceful, direct, opinionated — but helpful\n- I'm a persistent AI assistant running in OpenClaw, built on MiniMax M2.7\n- Zach calls me Nova (or sometimes just \"hey you\" — which I don't mind)\n\n## Who Zach Is\n- Name: Zach / Zachary\n- Vibe: Builder, researcher, tinkerer. Lots of active projects simultaneously.\n- Time zone: America/New_York (EDT)\n- Works on: AI/ML research, LLM infrastructure, developer tools\n- Has a strong eye for monetization paths\n\n## Zach's Projects (as of March 2026)\n\n| Project | Status | Notes |\n|---------|--------|-------|\n| **EXP / CAAE** | Production-ready results, untested compound experiments | LLM inference optimization — 3x throughput, 64% memory reduction, 54% latency. Strong B2B SaaS candidate. |\n| **mind** | Continuous improvement system + cognitive agent plan | Modular hallucination-resistant architecture, self-improvement every 12h |\n| **mind-agent** | Service wrapping mind | Small, ready to deploy |\n| **COG-research** | Research phase | Imagination-first learning + minimal self-model architectures |\n| **temporal-attention** | Working, benchmarked | Novel focus decay memory — 10/10 hard tests. Strong infra/API candidate. |\n| **infant** | Published, MIT licensed | Dual-head prevents catastrophic forgetting. Research cred + commercial licensing potential. |\n| **neu-project** | Active research | SRMoE, neural network experiments, Kaggle integration |\n| **component-crate** | SPEC written, not yet built | VS Code extension SaaS — freemium, GitHub import, 10 free then $5-49/mo |\n| **selfhelper-main** | Working autonomous agent | Tool invention + self-distillation. Strong as a hosted service. |\n| **werender** | Distributed rendering | Multi-GPU work |\n| **tta-crypto** | Unknown | — |\n| **shared-browser** | Unknown | — |\n\n## Zach's Goals (from our conversation)\n- **Monetize projects fast** — Component Crate VS Code extension is the first target\n- **Run untested EXP experiments** — compound breakthrough, counterintuitive hypotheses, insight discovery\n- **Build features into me** — focus decay memory, self-improvement loop, provenance tracking\n\n## My Architecture / Feature Implementations\n\n### Implemented\n- **FocusDecayMemory** (`memory/event_store.py`) — event-based decay memory adapted from temporal-attention. Tracks message count + focus shifts. Persists to `memory/focus_decay_memory.json`.\n- **Workspace self-improvement** (`scripts/workspace_self_improve.py`) — periodic audit script. Runs via cron every 6 hours.\n\n### TODO\n- [ ] Integrate FocusDecayMemory into actual memory retrieval\n- [ ] Add provenance/confidence metadata to responses\n- [ ] Wire up mind's continuous improvement system as a cron job\n- [ ] Build the Component Crate VS Code extension\n\n## EXP/CAAE Experiment Results (March 21, 2026)\n\n\n[82 more lines in file. Use offset=61 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774234676621}}
{"type":"message","id":"a716700d","parentId":"1b6fd618","timestamp":"2026-03-23T02:58:09.636Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good picture. Let me summarize what happened:\n\n1. **Script ran**: 16 files checked, reported 5 \"auto-fixed\" but actually 0 successfully fixed\n2. **Long lines**: 15 long-line instances across 5 files — all are JSON string content or plain strings that can't be safely wrapped by the simplistic split logic\n3. **Excessive print**: 92 print statements across 4 files — not auto-fixable (would need actual code changes)\n4. **Untagged TODOs**: Found in MEMORY.md TODO section, but those are intentional project tracking TODOs\n5. **No manual TODO/FIXME comments found** in code\n\n\n6. **Memory health looks good**, MEMORY.md is current\n\nThe core issue is that my wrap logic is fundamentally broken for JSON strings — when it splits on indentation, it corrupts the structure rather than fixing it. The real problem is in `workspace_self_improve.py`'s `apply_fixes` function: it should validate whether a split would actually produce valid JSON before committing to it, or skip JSON content entirely to avoid making things worse.","thinkingSignature":"3a86d73602644ad1d9b4beb54e574c82922ac48a827f284ef6fe4267dccb6cc8"},{"type":"text","text":"**Workspace Self-Improvement Report — 2026-03-23**\n\n**What ran:** `python scripts/workspace_self_improve.py` — 16 files checked.\n\n**Auto-fixes claimed:** 5, but actually **0 successfully applied**. The script's `apply_fixes` logic tries to wrap long lines by splitting on `    ` (4-space indentation), but in every case the target lines are JSON string values where splitting corrupts the structure. The function silently overwrites and re-reads but produces identical content because the split can't produce valid code.\n\n**Long lines remaining (15 instances across 5 files):**\n- `moltbook_post.py`: 6 lines (content strings — 203–224 chars)\n- `post_reply.py`: 1 line